#, no-wrap
msgid "!!! warning \"Pound Missing from EPEL-9\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:16
#, no-wrap
msgid "    As of this writing, on Rocky Linux 9.0, Pound cannot be installed from the EPEL repository. While there are sources out there for SRPM packages, we can't verify the integrity of these sources. For this reason, we do not recommend installing the Pound proxy server on Rocky Linux 9.0 at this time. This may change if the EPEL once again picks up Pound.  Use this procedure specifically for Rocky Linux 8.x versions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:20
#, no-wrap
msgid "Pound is a web server agnostic reverse proxy and load balancer that is very easy to setup and manage. It does not use a web service itself, but does listen on the web service ports (http, https). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:22
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now, there are a lot of proxy server options, some referenced in these documentation pages. There is a document on using [HAProxy here](haproxy_apache_lxd.md) and there have been references in other documents to using Nginx for a reverse proxy.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:24
#, no-wrap
msgid "Load balancing services are quite useful for a busy web server environment. Many proxy servers, including the previously mentioned HAProxy, can be used for many service types. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:26
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the case of Pound, it can only be used for web services, but it's good at what it does.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:30
#, no-wrap
msgid "The following are minimum requirements for using this procedure:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "A desire to load balance between a few websites, or a desire to learn a new tool do do the same.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "The ability to execute commands as the root user or use `sudo` to get there.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "Familiarity with a command-line editor. We are using `vi` or `vim` here, but feel free to substitute in your favorite editor.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "Comfort with changing the listen ports on a few types of web servers.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "We are assuming that both the Nginx and the Apache servers are already installed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "We are assuming that you are using Rocky Linux servers or containers for everything here.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "While we make all kinds of statements regarding `https` below, this guide only deals with the `http` service. To properly do `https`, you'll need to configure your pound server with a real certificate from a real certificate authority.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:42
#, no-wrap
msgid "    If you don't have either of these servers installed, you can do so on a container environment (LXD or Docker) or on bare metal, and get them up and running. For this procedure, you merely need to install them with their respective packages, and enable and start the services. We won't be modifying them significantly in any way.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:46
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```\n"
"    dnf -y install nginx && systemctl enable --now nginx\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:48
#, no-wrap
msgid "    or\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:52
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```\n"
"    dnf -y install httpd && systemctl enable --now httpd\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:56
#, no-wrap
msgid "For this procedure, we are going to be using two web servers (known as back end servers), one running Nginx (192.168.1.111) and one running Apache (192.168.1.108). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "Our Pound server (192.168.1.103) will be considered the gateway. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:60
#, no-wrap
msgid "We will be switching our listen ports on both of the back end servers to 8080 for the Nginx server and 8081 for the Apache server. Everything will be detailed below as we go, so no need to worry about these for the moment.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:64
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Remember to change the associated IPs to whatever they are in your own environment and substitute them where applicable throughout this procedure.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:65
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing the Pound Server"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:68
#, no-wrap
msgid "To install Pound, we need to first install the EPEL (Extra Packages for Enterprise Linux) and run updates in case there is something new with EPEL:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "dnf -y install epel-release && dnf -y update\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "Then just install Pound. (Yes, that's a capital \"P\"):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:75
#, no-wrap
msgid "dnf -y install Pound\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:79
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring Pound"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:82
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now that the packages are installed we need to configure Pound. We will be using `vi` to update this, but if you prefer `nano` or something else, go ahead and substitute that in:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:83
#, no-wrap
msgid "vi /etc/pound.cfg\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:88
#, no-wrap
msgid "The file is set up with default information in it, which makes it easy to see most of the default components of Pound:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:89
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"User \"pound\"\n"
"Group \"pound\"\n"
"Control \"/var/lib/pound/pound.cfg\"\n"
"\n"
"ListenHTTP\n"
"    Address 0.0.0.0\n"
"    Port 80\n"
"End\n"
"\n"
"ListenHTTPS\n"
"    Address 0.0.0.0\n"
"    Port    443\n"
"    Cert    \"/etc/pki/tls/certs/pound.pem\"\n"
"End\n"
"\n"
"Service\n"
"    BackEnd\n"
"        Address 127.0.0.1\n"
"        Port    8000\n"
"    End\n"
"\n"
"    BackEnd\n"
"        Address 127.0.0.1\n"
"        Port    8001\n"
"    End\n"
"End\n"
msgstr ""

