"    BackEnd\n"
"        Address 192.168.1.117\n"
"        Port    8080\n"
"\tPriority 9\n"
"    End\n"
"\n"
"    BackEnd\n"
"        Address 192.168.1.108\n"
"        Port    8081\n"
"    End\n"
"    Emergency\n"
"\t   Address 192.168.1.104\n"
"\t   Port\t8000\n"
"   End\n"
"End\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:255
#, no-wrap
msgid "This server might only display a message that says, \"Down For Maintenance\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:256
#, no-wrap
msgid "Security Considerations"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:259
#, no-wrap
msgid "Something that most documents dealing with load balancing proxy servers will not deal with are the security issues. For instance, if this is a public facing web server, you will need to have the `http` and `https` services open to the world on the load balancing proxy. But what about the \"BackEnd\" servers? \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:261
#, no-wrap
msgid "Those should only need to be accessed by their ports from the Pound server itself, but since the Pound server is redirecting to 8080 or 8081 on the BackEnd servers, and since the BackEnd servers have `http` listening on those subsequent ports, you can just use the service names for the firewall commands on those BackEnd servers.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:263
#, no-wrap
msgid "In this section we will deal with those concerns, and the `firewalld` commands needed to lock everything down.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:267
#, no-wrap
msgid "    We are assuming that you have direct access to the servers in question and are not remote to them. If you are remote, take extreme caution when removing services from a `firewalld` zone!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:269
#, no-wrap
msgid "    You could lock yourself out of your server by accident.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:270
#, no-wrap
msgid "Firewall - Pound Server"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:273
#, no-wrap
msgid "For the Pound server, as noted above, we want to allow `http` and `https` from the world. You will need to consider whether `ssh` needs to be allowed from the world or not. If you are local to the server, this is probably **NOT** the case. We are assuming that the server here is available via your local network and that you have direct access to it, so we will be locking down `ssh` to our LAN IPs.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:275
#, no-wrap
msgid "To accomplish the above, we will use the built-in firewall for Rocky Linux, `firewalld` and the `firewall-cmd` command structure. For simplicity sake, we will also use two of the built-in zones, \"public\" and \"trusted\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:277
#, no-wrap
msgid "Let's start by adding our source IPs to the \"trusted\" zone. This is our LAN here (in our example: 192.168.1.0/24):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:278
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --zone=trusted --add-source=192.168.1.0/24 --permanent\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:283
#, no-wrap
msgid "Then, let's add the `ssh` service to the zone:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:284
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --zone=trusted --add-service=ssh --permanent\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:289
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once all of this is completed, reload the firewall with:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:295
#, no-wrap
msgid "And then list out the zone so that you can see everything with `firewall-cmd --zone=trusted --list-all` which should give you something like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:296
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"trusted (active)\n"
"  target: ACCEPT\n"
"  icmp-block-inversion: no\n"
"  interfaces:\n"
"  sources: 192.168.1.0/24\n"
"  services: ssh\n"
"  ports:\n"
"  protocols:\n"
"  forward: no\n"
"  masquerade: no\n"
"  forward-ports:\n"
"  source-ports:\n"
"  icmp-blocks:\n"
"  rich rules:\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:315
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next we need to make changes to the \"public\" zone, which by default has the `ssh` service enabled. This needs to be carefully removed (again, we are assuming that you are **NOT** remote to the server here!) with the following:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:316
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --zone=public --remove-service=ssh --permanent\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:320
#, no-wrap
msgid "We also need to add `http` and `https` services:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:321
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/firewalld.md:280
#, no-wrap
msgid "firewall-cmd --zone=public --add-service=http --add-service=https --permanent\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:326
#, no-wrap
msgid "Then we need to reload the firewall before you can see the changes:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:332
#, no-wrap
msgid "And then list out the public zone with `firewall-cmd --zone=public --list-all` which should show you something like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:333
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"public\n"
"  target: default\n"
"  icmp-block-inversion: no\n"
"  interfaces:\n"
"  sources:\n"
"  services: cockpit dhcpv6-client http https\n"
"  ports:\n"
"  protocols:\n"
"  forward: no\n"
"  masquerade: no\n"
"  forward-ports:\n"
"  source-ports:\n"
"  icmp-blocks:\n"
"  rich rules:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:351
#, no-wrap
msgid "Within our lab environment, those are the only changes we need to make to our pound server load balancer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:352
#, no-wrap
msgid "Firewall - Back End Servers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:355
#, no-wrap
msgid "For the \"BackEnd\" servers, we do not need to allow access from the world for anything and definitely not for our listen ports that the load balancer will be using. We will need to allow `ssh` from the LAN IPs, and `http` and `https` from our pound load balancer. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:357
#, no-wrap
msgid "That's pretty much it. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:359
#, no-wrap
msgid "Again, we are going to add the `ssh` service to our \"trusted\" zone, with the essentially the same commands we used for our pound server. Then we are going to add a zone called \"balance\" that we will use for the remaining `http` and `https`, and set the source IPs to that of the load balancer. Are you having fun yet?\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:361
#, no-wrap
msgid "To be quick, let's use all of those commands that we used for the \"trusted\" zone in a single set of commands:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:362
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"firewall-cmd --zone=trusted --add-source=192.168.1.0/24 --permanent\n"
"firewall-cmd --zone=trusted --add-service=ssh --permanent\n"
"firewall-cmd --reload\n"
"firewall-cmd --zone=trusted --list-all\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:370
#, no-wrap
msgid "After, the \"trusted\" zone should look like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:389
#, no-wrap
msgid "Again, test your `ssh` rule from an IP on the LAN, and then remove the `ssh` service from the \"public\" zone. **Remember our warning from above, and do this only if you have local access to the server!**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:390
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"firewall-cmd --zone=public --remove-service=ssh --permanent\n"
"firewall-cmd --reload\n"
"firewall-cmd --zone=public --list-all\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:397
#, no-wrap
msgid "The public zone should now look like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:398
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"public\n"
"  target: default\n"
"  icmp-block-inversion: no\n"
"  interfaces:\n"
"  sources:\n"
"  services: cockpit dhcpv6-client\n"
"  ports:\n"
"  protocols:\n"
"  forward: no\n"
"  masquerade: no\n"
"  forward-ports:\n"
"  source-ports:\n"
"  icmp-blocks:\n"
"  rich rules:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:416
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now let's add that new zone to deal with `http` and `https`. Remember that the source IP here needs to only be our load balancer (in our example: 192.168.1.103):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:420
#, no-wrap
msgid "    A new zone must be added with the `--permanent` option and cannot be used until the firewall is reloaded. Also, don't forget to `--set-target=ACCEPT` for this zone!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:421
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"firewall-cmd --new-zone=balance --permanent\n"
"firewall-cmd --reload\n"
"firewall-cmd --zone=balance --set-target=ACCEPT\n"
"firewall-cmd --zone=balance --add-source=192.168.1.103 --permanent\n"
"firewall-cmd --zone=balance --add-service=http --add-service=https --permanent\n"
"firewall-cmd --reload\n"
"firewall-cmd --zone=balance --list-all\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:432
#, no-wrap
msgid "The result:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:433
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"balance (active)\n"
"  target: ACCEPT\n"
"  icmp-block-inversion: no\n"
"  interfaces:\n"
"  sources: 192.168.1.103\n"
"  services: http https\n"
"  ports:\n"
"  protocols:\n"
"  forward: no\n"
"  masquerade: no\n"
"  forward-ports:\n"
"  source-ports:\n"
"  icmp-blocks:\n"
"  rich rules:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:451
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now repeat those steps on the other web server back end.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/proxies/pound.md:453
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once you have your firewall rules added to everything, test your pound server again from your workstation browser.\n"
msgstr ""

